{ Before this tournament I set out the following goals for myself:

1) Play the spicy options that are positionally desirable even if I can't calculate it all out. Trust in the intuition.

2) Broad, not deep. I'd like to not miss my opponent's moves the entire time.

3) Don't ever play like it's hopeless. If it feels hopeless, assume that's just in my head and play as if I'm totally in the game.

My opponent was a 15 years old NM. He's an active member of a chess improvement discord that I'm also a member of. It came up that he occasionally streams on twitch as LSChess. }
1. e4 { [%clk 1:30:00] } 1... c5 { [%clk 1:30:00] } 2. Nf3 { [%clk 1:31:00] } 2... d6 { [%clk 1:31:00] } 3. d4 { [%clk 1:31:00] } 3... cxd4 { [%clk 1:31:00] } 4. Nxd4 { [%clk 1:31:00] } 4... Nf6 { [%clk 1:31:00] } 5. Nc3 { [%clk 1:31:00] } 5... Nc6 { My first OTB game against the Classical Sicilian. In the post-mortem, my opponent admitted that this was his first time trying out the opening OTB, having only done some deep study of it. He's historically mostly been a Najdorf player. } { [%clk 1:32:00] } 6. Bg5 { [%clk 1:30:00] } 6... e6 { [%clk 1:32:00] } 7. Qd2 { [%clk 1:29:00] } 7... a6 { [%clk 1:32:00] } 8. O-O-O { The main line of the Richter-Rauzer. I will admit that my knowledge of this opening is not nearly as strong as others. } { [%clk 1:29:00] } 8... Be7!? { Threats of Nxe4 loom if white isn't attentive. I'm now out of book. } { [%clk 1:32:00] } (8... Bd7!? { The main move. During the game I wasn't sure what the difference was between these two developing moves. }) 9. f3!? { I thought this was totally normal, but apparently black already scores well here according to the masters DB. } { [%clk 1:28:00] } (9. Kb1! { The theory move to play here. } 9... Nxd4 10. Qxd4 Bd7 (10... b5?! 11. e5! $14 { This is the most correct way to play as white. } { Arjun, Kalyan - Samant, Aditya S, 1-0, 15th Paracin Open A 2022, https://lichess.org/5sfukO1l }) 11. f3 $10 { Transposing to theory I know in the main line. }) (9. f4!? Bd7 10. Nf3 $10 { This would transition to a line against Bd7 that I somewhat recently stopped playing. It was simply too forcing for my taste. }) 9... Nxd4 { A normal reaction upon seeing f3. The queen does not want to be dragged up to d4 in most lines. } { [%clk 1:32:00] } 10. Qxd4 { [%clk 1:28:00] } 10... b5 { [%clk 1:32:00] } 11. h4 { All I know is that white should be doing some sort of English attack here to justify f3. But the bishop on g5 is misplaced in many lines since (1) it's loose after h5, and (2) it is blocking the g5 push. } { [%clk 1:26:00] } 11... O-O?! { It's my understanding that black should delay castling kingside into the attack. } { [%clk 1:32:00] } (11... Bb7 12. Kb1 Qc7 13. h5 h6 14. Be3 $10 { A more thematic way for black to play. }) 12. h5?! { It took me almost 20 minutes to pull the trigger on this move. Ultimately it's overrated, but I calculated that it doesn't lose in the center by force in any way. } { [%clk 1:07:00] } (12. Kb1! { The correct way forward. } 12... Bb7 { During the game I didn't know what to do next since h5 might run into Nxe4 issues and Qd2 allows Ne2. } 13. Qd2! b4!? 14. Ne2 d5 (14... a5!? 15. Nd4 Qc7 16. g4 Rfc8 $14 { Look at all these healthy moves that white can make before touching the h pawn again. }) 15. e5 Nd7 $14 { A better version of the game since the DSB trade helps white. }) 12... h6 { I was happy to see my opponent create a hook for me to later attack on the kingside. Unfortunately, nothing came of this hook during the game. } { [%clk 1:32:00] } (12... e5?! 13. Qd3! (13. Qd2?! b4! 14. Ne2 Be6 $17) 13... b4 14. Bxf6! { With the queen on d3 and not d2, we can play this intermezzo. Most of my 20 minute think was spent finding this refutation to black's quick d5 break. } 14... Bxf6 15. Nd5 $14) 13. Be3 { [%clk 1:07:00] } (13. Bxf6? Bxf6! 14. Qxd6 Qa5! $17 { b4 is coming. Rd8 is coming. Bxc3 is coming. White has no development and black is already launching a huge attack. } (14... Qxd6?! 15. Rxd6 Bb7 $10 { During the post-mortem my opponent admitted that he knew endgames like this were often 0.0 simply because of the bishop pair. })) 13... Bb7 { [%clk 1:30:00] } 14. Qd2!? { Prophylaxis against black's d5 break. } { [%clk 1:04:00] } (14. g4!? { The straightforward attack gets smacked down. } 14... e5! 15. Qd2 b4 16. Ne2? (16. Na4!? $13 { So maybe this weird move is required? I thought for sure Bc6 would target this sidelined knight and I would regret this. } 16... d5!? { Possibly still playable. } (16... a5!? { Defending the b pawn and preparing Bc6. })) (16. Nd5?! Nxd5 17. exd5 a5 $15 { I didn't like this structure during the game. I'd rather have the backwards d6 pawn to target. }) 16... d5 $17 { And I'm getting overrun in the center. }) 14... b4 { My opponent decides to disturb my knight on c3, taking advantage of the weakness of my last move. I wasn't unhappy yet though as this also creates a crisis on b4. } { [%clk 1:27:00] } 15. Ne2 { [%clk 1:02:00] } 15... d5!? { Black hurries to get in the d5 break, but since I can respond with e5, I thought this was overrated. } { [%clk 1:26:00] } (15... a5!? 16. Kb1 Qc7 17. Nd4 $10 { White is comfortable here, since d5 is still not on the cards. } 17... d5?! 18. e5! Qxe5?? 19. Bf4 $18) (15... Qc7!? { Might hang the b pawn too. But just to show that this doesn't prepare d5: } 16. Nd4 d5? 17. e5! Qxe5?? 18. Bf4! $18) 16. e5 { [%clk 1:00:00] } 16... Nd7 { [%clk 1:26:00] } 17. f4 { And now we get a French position I wasn't unhappy to play. } { [%clk 0:58:00] } 17... Nb6! { The Ding maneuver in the French! The knight is heading to c4 (and possibly even b2) with disastrous effects. I didn't see this coming. Only now did I start to worry that I was slightly worse. } { [%clk 1:24:00] } (17... Nc5!? { The main move I saw coming. } 18. Nd4 (18. Qxb4?? Nd3+ $19 { [%cal Gd3b4,Gd3c1] }) 18... Ne4 19. Qe1 $10 { My expectations. Bd3 is coming and both sides have a lot of play here. }) 18. Qe1!? { No DSB for you! } { [%clk 0:42:00] } (18. Nd4!? { The most normal move. } 18... Nc4 19. Qf2 { I thought this was bad for white for two reasons. Firstly, Nxe3 wins the bishop pair and the DSB can open up after black breaks with a timely f6. Secondly, the knight doesn't have to take on e3 and the queenside attack is quite strong.
However, after analyzing with the engine, I now appreciate that black's LSB is a true French bishop. It's not ever contributing unless Ba6 is played, in which case black doesn't keep the bishop pair. Moreover, even without the DSB, I can play for the g5 pawn break as a pawn sacrifice. Opening up lines against black's king is easy. Opening up lines against white's king is harder. } (19. Bxc4? dxc4 $17 { c3 and b3 are killing white here. The LSB has opened up too. }) 19... Nxe3!? (19... a5!? $15 { I can't ever play Bxc4 here, giving black a huge queenside pawn phalanx, so black can just get on with it and hold my DSB hostage. }) (19... Qc7!? $15 { Another way to stick it to white. Black's queenside play isn't going anywhere. } 20. Kb1 a5 21. Bc1 a4 22. g4 $13) 20. Qxe3 a5 $15) (18. b3?! a5 $17 { I assumed this was crushing for black. a4 is coming too quickly. Both of us discussed this position during the post-mortem and agreed black was having all the fun. Perhaps this is a hasty assumption though. } 19. Nd4 a4 20. Kb1 axb3 21. cxb3 $10 { GM Hambleton's suggestion where perhaps white is relatively safe. }) 18... Nc4 { [%clk 1:21:00] } 19. Bd4 { Following through with my decision to play the spicy options when given the chance. I'm not losing the bishop pair, and my pieces are clunky, but given a few moves I can sort them all out. If only my opponent could hand me back a little time... } { [%clk 0:42:00] } 19... Qa5?! { Even during the game, both of us appreciated that this was just a waste of tempo.
This is the problem with playing sensible moves too quickly and not stopping to calculate. If my opponent had spent 10 minutes determining what was the best way to execute the attack, he would have seen this queen is just in the way of the a pawn. That's not necessarily something you can divine instantly. } { [%clk 1:19:00] } (19... a5! { Getting on with it is obviously correct in retrospect. } 20. Kb1 a4 21. Nc1 $15 { Black is up a tempo compared to the game. The attack is raging and white's attack has barely started. }) 20. Kb1 { Black just forced me to make a move I wanted to make anyway. } { [%clk 0:42:00] } 20... Rfc8 { [%clk 1:18:00] } 21. Nc1 { [%clk 0:39:00] } 21... Qc7 { The queen returns to where it belongs. a5+a4 is still the pawn storm to play. } { [%clk 1:15:00] } 22. Bd3 { [%clk 0:36:00] } 22... a5 { A critical position. I'm down more than 30 minutes and have a tough position. Black's textbook attack is coming with a4-a3 and Nb2. Do I have time for g4-g5 or do I need to rush things with f5? } { [%clk 1:14:00] } 23. f5!? { Ultimately I decided to rush through with this breakthrough simply because it's the more forcing way to play. Black does not have time to open up the queenside.
If I had this position again, I would probably go for the other break in the position (g4-g5) even though hours of analysis have not given me true insight into whether or not it leads to a KO (or even a better position than the one I got in the game!). } { [%clk 0:34:00] } (23. g4!? a4 24. g5 { The continuation I would have chosen in a blitz game since white has some real chances to blow open the kingside by sacrificing this pawn that black doesn't have to take. During the game, I couldn't figure out all the variations here since black can choose the nature of this continuation.
Honestly, having analyzed this position for over three hours, there are still too many variations with shockingly different races to be able to clearly determine which continuation is objectively best. Regardless, every high rated player I've shown this game to agrees that they would have tried g4-g5 instead of my f5, simply because the bishop on g5 is too strong in the game. I agree. } 24... hxg5!? { The most natural move, and what I assumed my opponent would play during the game. } (24... a3? { Black's main way to open up the position can simply be ignored. } 25. gxh6!! (25. b3!? Nb2 { I was scared of this position during the game but for no reason. White doesn't need to lose c2 or the exchange. } 26. Rd2! (26. Bxb2? axb2 27. Kxb2 hxg5! $17 { Too many lines have been opened up on the queenside. White hasn't yet had the same fun on the kingside. Moreover, black's DSB cannot be allowed to reach g5, where it targets the key defender: the knight on c1. } 28. h6!? g6 29. Qg3!? gxf4 30. Qxf4 f5!! $17 { The queen being undefended on f4 prevents en passant, and so black keeps the kingside closed. }) 26... Nxd3?! (26... hxg5!? 27. Qg3! { Preventing Bg5. } 27... gxf4?! (27... Qd8!? 28. f5 { Again preventing Bg5. } 28... Nxd3 29. Nxd3 $14 { The threat is h6 with more lines opening. }) 28. Qxf4 Nxd3 29. Nxd3 $16 { The kingside is too open here, and black has no attack on the closed queenside. }) 27. Nxd3 $16 { c2 is secure and now white gets to have their fun. }) 25... axb2 { With an absolute mess that apparently works out for white. } 26. Qg3!! bxc1=Q+ (26... Na3+?! 27. Kxb2 $18) 27. Kxc1 g6 (27... Kf8?! 28. hxg7+ Ke8 29. g8=Q+ $18) 28. hxg6 $18 { Black's king is on the chopping block and white's king is totally fine. }) (24... b3?! { Opening up lines, but white doesn't have any issues if we just take what's offered. } 25. cxb3 { Keeps the a file semi-closed. } (25. axb3? axb3 26. Nxb3 Qc6 $13 { The a file could be deadly. } { [%cal Gc6a4] }) 25... a3!? (25... axb3?! 26. Nxb3! $16 { It's scary around my king, but does black even have a threat? } (26. a3? Nxa3+ 27. bxa3 Ba6! { Removing the defender of c2. } 28. Qe2 Bxa3 $19 { I hate this for white. I can only assume there's a knockout somewhere. })) 26. gxh6 axb2 27. Ne2! (27. Bxb2?! Nxb2 $13 { This is much less clear. The dark squares are too tender. }) 27... Na3+ 28. Kxb2 Nc4+ 29. Ka1 $18 { White is fine on the queenside and black's king is still getting killed. }) 25. h6!? { If taking on g5 doesn't help, then this is the most normal way to open up the kingside. } (25. fxg5?! Bxg5! 26. h6!? { The most thematic way to open it all up. Before black can secure the kingside with Bh6. } (26. Qg3!? Bh6 $17 { No breakthrough is possible anymore since the h file remains closed. }) 26... gxh6! { Unfortunately, I couldn't find a way here to break through. Black's king is running to f8 in every variation, and I don't see the justification for sacrificing two pawns. } (26... Bxh6?? 27. Rxh6! gxh6 28. Qxb4!! $18 { Preventing the king from escaping. The rook will next arrive on g1 with a thud. }) 27. Qg3?! (27. Qxb4!? Rab8 $13 { [%cal Gd3c4] }) (27. Rxh6? Bxh6 28. Qh4 Bxc1! $19 { And nothing seems to work out for white. The king is too slippery as he runs away to the queenside next. }) 27... Kf8 $13) (25. Qg3?! b3! (25... gxf4? { Opening up the kingside, even at the cost of a tempo, is not smart. } 26. Qxf4 { [%cal Gh5h6,Gd1g1] } 26... b3 { If black continues in the thematic manner, white finally breaks through first. } 27. cxb3 a3 28. Rhg1! axb2 29. Bxb2! Nxb2 30. Qh6! $18 { Both Qh7 and Qg7 are deadly threats. }) 26. cxb3 a3! $13 { Once more, this break is just too confusing for me to clearly evaluate. Black does not need to open up the kingside. } (26... axb3?! 27. Nxb3 $16)) (25. Qg1!? gxf4 26. h6 g6 27. Bxg6) 25... g6 { There doesn't seem to be any way to open up the position here either though. If white does nothing, then the b3 breakthrough is still happening on the queenside. } 26. fxg5!? (26. f5? { Looks flashy but doesn't work. } 26... exf5 27. h7+ Kh8! 28. e6+ f6! $19) 26... b3! (26... Bxg5?! $14 { Perhaps white can use the g file here. }) 27. cxb3 a3! $13 { This is once again a mess though where black is having all the fun against my king. }) 23... Bg5! { Getting out of f6 ideas and preventing the g5 break forever. On a good day, black even has Bf4 to win e5.
GM Hambleton already liked black here and figured that seeing Bg5 was enough to want to enter the murky g4-g5 lines instead. } { [%clk 1:11:00] } (23... a4?! 24. f6! gxf6 25. exf6 Bf8 26. Rh4 $13 { The race continues but white should be happy here. } { [%cal Gh4g4] }) 24. Rf1 { The rook prevents Bf4 and will often stand well on the f file after fxe6. At least a4 is not playable without the b pawn dropping, right? } { [%clk 0:23:00] } (24. f6?! { Now this move accomplishes nothing. } 24... a4 $17) (24. Rh4? { During the game I was getting desperate. I even considered Rg4 just to sacrifice the exchange and break through to the kingside...
