{ My 15 year old opponent is the famous prodigy, Rachael Li, known for becoming the youngest NM woman at the age of 9. I can only assume something beyond the board was going on in her life because she was upset when I greeted her before the game, upset when I offered a draw during the game, and upset when I asked for a quick analysis session after the game. }
1. e4 { [%clk 1:30:00] } 1... c5 { [%clk 1:30:00] } 2. Nf3 { [%clk 1:31:00] } 2... e6 { [%clk 1:30:00] } 3. d4 { [%clk 1:31:00] } 3... cxd4 { [%clk 1:31:00] } 4. Nxd4 { [%clk 1:32:00] } 4... a6 { The Sicilian Kan } { [%clk 1:31:00] } 5. Bd3 { [%clk 1:32:00] } 5... Nf6 { [%clk 1:30:00] } (5... Bc5 $10 { Objectively the best way to equalize. But I like keeping tension in the position, even if I'm playing someone 300 points higher rated than me! }) 6. O-O { [%clk 1:32:00] } 6... Qc7 { [%clk 1:30:00] } 7. c3!? { Atypical - played after 6 minutes think. I don't think this was opening prep, but it has some merit. By defending the knight directly, Nc6 and Bc5 are now ineffective. Moreover, the thematic b5 move can now be struck at instantly with a4! So black can only really "punish" this move by playing normally and arguing that the b1 knight is going to be worse than if it had the c3 square. } { [%clk 1:26:00] } (7. Qe2!? $14 { The main move and what I play as white. In my opinion, white has a slight advantage in all lines. }) 7... Be7!? { I didn't want to commit the d pawn to d6 just yet. Maybe there's a world in which case d5 is good for me. } { [%clk 1:24:00] } (7... Nc6!? { The other normal way to play. But now with c3 in, white doesn't need to respond to this move. } 8. Qe2 $10) (7... b5?! 8. a4! $16 { This is one of the positional threats white has. Lines are opening and black doesn't have the necessary development to keep it all together. }) (7... d5?! { Already playable, but after: } 8. exd5 Nxd5 $14 { Black is fine, but white just gets a healthy 3 vs 2 on the kingside. I'm still lagging in development, and my LSB in particular will suffer unless I can play e5, which opens up my king. It's all a bit too early to play this break. }) 8. Nd2 { [%clk 1:22:00] } 8... d6 { I saw that f4 and N2f3 or Nc4 are coming, so e5 must be prevented. This is a convenient way to do it. But now I'm admitting I don't want to play Nc6 anymore. } { [%clk 1:20:00] } (8... d5?! { The freeing break is again playable, but probably overrated for black. } 9. exd5 Nxd5 10. Ne4!? $14 { Again, white is not hugely better, but gets a lead in development for free. } (10. N2f3!? $14)) 9. f4 { [%clk 1:16:00] } (9. Nc4?! { All bark, no bite. } 9... b5 10. Ne3 Bb7 $15) 9... Nbd7 { [%clk 1:20:00] } 10. Qe2 { White is preparing N2f3 and e5 to kick my pieces around. } { [%clk 1:12:00] } 10... g6!? { A move I'm particularly proud of, played after a 17 minute think. It's incredibly weakening to my kingside to make this move, but by preventing Nf5 directly, white's e5 thrust can now be prevented with our own e5. } { [%clk 1:03:00] } (10... O-O!? { I didn't believe it during the game, but we can get away with castling. White's e5 threat is still slightly overrated. } 11. N2f3 { e5 is coming, whether I like it or not. } 11... Nc5! { I underestimated this tempo during the game. } 12. Bc2 { I was thinking maybe there was beautiful shot here during the game to avoid e5 from murdering me, but I couldn't see it. } (12. e5? Nxd3 13. exf6 Nxc1 14. Raxc1 Bxf6 $17) 12... e5! { Only in analysis do I see this is playable too. } (12... g6?! 13. e5 Nh5 14. g4 Ng7 $16 { I hated this position. }) (12... b5? 13. e5! Ne8 14. b4 Nb7 15. Qe4! $18 { I was sure I was dying here. } (15. f5!? $16)) 13. b4!? (13. Nf5?! Bxf5 14. exf5 $15 { White's attack is no more and so black just has a good center. }) (13. fxe5!? dxe5 14. Nf5 Bxf5 15. exf5 e4 $15) 13... Ncxe4! 14. Bxe4 exd4 $17) 11. N2f3 { [%clk 1:06:00] } 11... e5! { White doesn't get a chance to play e5 themselves. The d5 weakness is a non-issue now that white's knight has gone to c3 since neither knight can easily reroute to d5. } { [%clk 1:03:00] } 12. Nb3?! { Neither knight can now reach d5, and my pawn center is killing practically every white minor piece. Black should be slightly better after normal moves. } { [%clk 1:05:00] } (12. fxe5!? dxe5 { As in the game, this was always playable for white. } 13. Nb3!? $10 { Transposes to the game. } (13. Nc2!? { Probably the better square, as we're trying to reroute to d5. But black does get a lead in development after: } 13... Nc5!? 14. Bc4!? $15 { Perhaps the e pawn is poison, but black is the one making threats after either b5 or Be6. } (14. Bh6?! Ng4! 15. Bg7?! Rg8 $17 { [%cal Gg8g7] }) 14... Ncxe4?! (14... Be6 $10) (14... b5 $10) 15. Bh6 $13 { Taking this pawn is a bit unnecessary. })) (12. Nc2!? $10 { The retreat I expected in the game. }) 12... b6!? { Less ambitious than b5, but solid. } { [%clk 1:00:00] } (12... b5!? { Giving white a hook on the queenside may not be so smart. } 13. a4?! { I didn't want to allow the queenside opening up when I haven't finished development yet. I didn't see during the game that it's not yet playable and that it is hard to get in at all. } (13. c4!? $10 { The other way to punish my setup. White more typically quickly gets a rook to the c file. Here, black probably has enough resources to be fine. }) (13. Kh1!? Bb7 14. a4 O-O! $10 { e4 is loose so again a4 is a bit overrated. I didn't calculate these ideas during the game, but probably this means that b5 is just as good or even better than b6 after all. }) 13... bxa4! 14. Rxa4?? Qb6+ $19) (12... exf4?! 13. Bxf4 Ne5 $14 { Possibly playable for black, since this is a common resource in similar positions. But why would I make both of white's knights and DSB happier for free? }) 13. Bd2 { [%clk 0:53:00] } 13... Bb7 { [%clk 1:00:00] } 14. a4 { She decides to put a clamp on my b5 expansion after all. I wasn't upset yet, but later in the game I regretted my a pawn being a target. } { [%clk 0:49:00] } 14... O-O { Castling into it, but I didn't believe white had any serious attack on my kingside. Obviously, I wish I had this same position but without having committed to g6 now that the knight is on b3. } { [%clk 0:55:00] } (14... Nh5?! { Another move I considered, but rejected simply because it sidelines my knight and asks white to play healthy moves. } 15. fxe5 dxe5 16. g3 $14) 15. fxe5 { Finally white pulls the trigger on this trade in the center. } { [%clk 0:46:00] } (15. f5? { White can't run me over on the kingside and abandon the center. } 15... gxf5! { I was happy to see that my signature move was working out for black here. Rather than my king being vulnerable, white is simply imploding their own center. } 16. Nh4!? (16. exf5?! e4! $18) 16... fxe4! 17. Nf5!? (17. Bh6?! exd3! $19 { White has no threats. }) 17... exd3! 18. Nxe7+ Kh8 $19 { White has no threats. }) 15... dxe5!? { Preventing both knights from using the d4 square. } { [%clk 0:54:00] } (15... Nxe5!? $10 { In earlier positions, this recapture was sometimes on my mind. But here, I wasn't sure I wanted to weaken the knight on f6 yet, nor allow the b3 knight back into the game via d4. }) 16. Bh6 { The timing of these moves by white made some sense to me during the game. Because white is gaining a tempo on my rook and not shooting into thin air, Ng4 is not really a thing. } { [%clk 0:45:00] } 16... Rfd8!? { Can't be a mistake compared to Rfe8, simply because the rook is better on the open file. But I do run into issues later once Bg5 puts my f6 knight in a pin. } { [%clk 0:46:00] } (16... Rfe8!? { In the long term, the rook doesn't want to be on e8. But this might save a tempo compared to the game by avoiding a later Bg5 pin. } 17. Rad1!? (17. Ng5?! { This move still fails. } 17... Bf8! 18. Bxf8 (18. Bc4?? Bxh6 19. Bxf7+ Kg7 20. Bxe8 Rxe8 $17) 18... Rxf8 $15) (17. Nfd2!? Bf8 18. Be3 $10 { A new option that black should be happy to play. Nc4 is coming with pressure on b6. }) 17... Bf8 18. Bg5 h6 19. Bh4 Bg7 $15 { Now black's knights can directly transfer to h5 and e6 one tempo faster. }) 17. Rad1 { During the game, I felt stuck here. I wanted to be better somehow based on my more active minor pieces, but couldn't find an active move to justify that eval. Eventually, I went for what I thought was an equal position. } { [%clk 0:40:00] } (17. Ng5?! Bf8! 18. Bxf8 (18. Bc4?? Bxh6! 19. Nxf7 Kg7! $19 { My king is safe and I'm winning material. }) 18... Rxf8 $15 { f7 is solidly defended and I've traded off the bad DSB. My king is only a little weak. }) 17... Bf8!? { This solid move tries to reclaim some of my weakened dark squares. I no longer felt that I was better in the game. } { [%clk 0:38:00] } (17... Bc6?! { One active attempt, but I was scared on the kingside by: } 18. Ng5!? { f7 is truly weak. } 18... b5!? (18... Bxa4? 19. Bc4 $16 { We do not want to go in for nonsense like this. }) (18... Bf8 19. Nxf7!? $13 { Even this move is crazy. }) 19. axb5 axb5 20. c4!? $13 { The position is now way too confusing to think that black has made progress. The a file by itself doesn't do anything. }) (17... Ng4!? { This move had my attention during the game. } 18. Bc1 $10 { But h3 is coming next, and my knight will just be kicked back to f6. I didn't see any way to wrestle the initiative here. Probably will transpose to the game after h3. }) (17... Nf8?! 18. Ng5! $14 { An annoying move. }) (17... Nc5?! { Trades a good knight for a poor knight that is dominated. Black's king is weakened too in some lines. } 18. Nxc5 Qxc5+!? (18... Bxc5+!? 19. Kh1 Ng4 20. Bg5 $14) 19. Be3 Qc7 20. Bg5 $14) 18. Bg5! { Of course white shouldn't rush to trade off black's bad bishop as then there is no further way to attack on the kingside. } { [%clk 0:39:00] } (18. Bxf8?! Rxf8 $15 { f7 is solidly defended and I've traded off black's bad DSB for white's good bishop. My king is only a little weak, but the dark squares in white's camp might matter. } (18... Nxf8?! { Weakens both f8 and f7. } 19. Ng5! $16 { With tempo on f6. The threats to f7 scared me during the game. Analysis confirmed that this is indeed great for white in combination with Bc4. })) 18... Bg7 { The king is safe. The knight on f6 is secure. But my bishop on g7 is now staring at my own pawn. If only I could get my knights to e6 and f4... } { [%clk 0:34:00] } (18... h6!? 19. Bh4 (19. Bxf6?! Nxf6 $17 { There are n