mes with no threats - white can make progress with the remaining pieces. }) (39. g4!? { This move seemed a bit desperate to me, but if you're actually scared about mating nets, it's probably the way to go. The pawn doesn't matter. } 39... hxg3 40. Nc7 Ng7 $16 { Black is once more tragically stuck. }) 39... Ng3 { [%clk 0:03:00] } 40. Rf2 { [%clk 0:06:00] } 40... Rxf2! { Except for one thing! } { [%clk 0:03:00] } 41. Kxf2 { [%clk 0:06:00] } 41... Ne4+! { At the end of the line, the c3 pawn is dropping. } { [%clk 0:03:00] } 42. Kf3 { [%clk 0:06:00] } 42... Nxc3 { In the game I had no idea if this was a fortress or not. But with Kf7 and Be7 coming, I thought I had good chances. Amazing. Both of us have no time and I'm quite close to creating some sort of fortress again. } { [%clk 0:03:00] } 43. Nc7?! { I didn't recognize that this obvious regrouping move was inaccurate during the game. } { [%clk 0:06:00] } (43. Rc8! { I didn't consider this move during the game, but it's the clear way to kill black. } 43... Nd5 44. Ke4 Kf7 45. Kxe5 $16 { The knight will re-enter the fray on c5, but black keeping the extra knights on the board means that there is some semblance of light square control. Therefore, white cannot simply march in on the light squares and checkmate me as in the game. }) 43... Kf7 { [%clk 0:03:00] } 44. Rd7+ { [%clk 0:04:00] } (44. Nxe6! Be7 { My snap thought during the game was that I was fine here but no white has some tricks still. } 45. Rc8! e4+! { Stockfish suggestion. } (45... Kxe6?! 46. Rxc3 $18 { A win. Similar to the game. }) 46. Kf4! (46. Kf2 e3+! 47. Kxe3 Nd5+ 48. Kd4 Kxe6) 46... Ne2+! (46... Nd5+?! 47. Ke5! $18) 47. Ke3 (47. Ke5! Bf6+ 48. Kd6 $16 { Stockfish recommendation. }) 47... Kxe6 48. Kxe2 Bg5 $16 { Real drawing chances here. A better version of the game due to the light square control. }) 44... Be7 { My position is compact. In the game I was struggling to evaluate this position as still winning for white. } { [%clk 0:03:00] } 45. Ke3 { [%clk