In retrospect, this move fails my 3rd objective of the tournament: "Don't ever play like it's hopeless. If it feels hopeless, assume that's just in my head and play as if I'm totally in the game." If I had played Na4, I might have still lost the game, but at least I wouldn't have given in as easily as I did. } { [%clk 0:03:00] } (45... Kf6!? { A better option. The knight doesn't get sidelined until it's forced to. } 46. Kd3!? (46. Ne8+?! Kf7 47. Nd6+?! (47. Nc7 Kf6 $10) 47... Kf8 48. Kd3 Nd5 49. Nc4 e4+! $10 { If anyone is making progress here, it's black. }) 46... Na4 47. Na6 Nb6 $10 { [%cal Gb6d5] }) (45... Na4?! { I couldn't quite bring myself to play such a passive move during the game. } 46. Nb5 { Ke4 and Nd6+ is coming. Since all of white's pieces are attacking me, I wasn't entirely sure if I have a fortress here. } (46. Ke4?? Nc5+ $19 { The point. Ke4 is prevented for one move. }) 46... Kf6 { I only got here during the game. Couldn't evaluate the position. } 47. Rc7! Nc5 48. Nc3 { This position is terrifying, but it's not entirely clear yet if white has a win here or not. } 48... h6!? 49. Kf3 { Rxc5 is now a threat. } (49. Ne4+?! Nxe4 50. Kxe4 Bb4 $10) 49... Nd3!? (49... Kf7!? 50. Ne4!? $16) (49... h5?? 50. Rxc5 Bxc5 51. Ne4+ Kf5 52. Nxc5 $18) 50. Ne4+ Kf7 51. Nd6+ Kf6 52. Nc4 h5 $16) 46. Nxd5 { [%clk 0:04:00] } 46... exd5 { [%clk 0:03:00] } 47. Rxd5 { [%clk 0:04:00] } 47... Bg5+! $10 { Draw offered by me and rejected by her. } { [%clk 0:03:00] } 48. Ke4 { [%clk 0:04:00] } 48... Bf4 { I saw this position before pulling the trigger on the knight trade. All my pawns will be defended after h6 to come. White is effectively down the two pawns.
So the real question is: can white mate black with just a king and rook if there is no such thing as Zugzwang? It was my impression during the game that this is not possible. Whenever I'm "forced" to walk opposite my opponent's king, I'll just not do that and move my bishop instead.
My opponent instructively shows me how this is just not the case. White is already winning. } { [%clk 0:03:00] } 49. Kf5 { [%clk 0:04:00] } 49... Ke7 { [%clk 0:02:00] } 50. Ra5 { [%clk 0:04:00] } (50. Rxe5+?? Bxe5 51. Kxe5 Kf7 52. Kf5 h6! 53. Kg4 Kg6 54. Kxh4 h5! 55. Kg3 Kf5! $10) 50... Kd6 { [%clk 0:02:00] } 51. Ke4 { [%clk 0:04:00] } 51... h6 { My bishop can defend all the pawns, but the problem is my king. } { [%clk 0:02:00] } (51... Kc6!? { I thought this king and pawn endgame might be lost with my king so far away. This is probably better defense. } 52. Ra6+!? (52. Rxe5?? Bxe5 53. Kxe5 Kc5 { Amazingly black is still drawing this one. } 54. Kf4 Kd4 55. Kg4 Ke3 56. Kxh4 Kf2 57. g4 Kg2 58. g5 Kf3 59. Kh5 Kg3 60. h4 Kh3 61. Kh6 Kxh4 62. Kxh7 Kxg5 $10) 52... Kc5! { Centralize the king! } 53. Ra7 h6 $13 { And white needs to go about mating me a whole different way. }) 52. Ra6+ { [%clk 0:04:00] } 52... Ke7?! { Now my king gets stuck though. } { [%clk 0:02:00] } (52... Kc5! { Centralize the king. Now this would have been better defense. } 53. Re6?! { This was the move I didn't want to allow. Again, I thought it was a winning king and pawn endgame from afar. } (53. Rf6!? { Threatening Rxf4 ideas if black isn't careful. } 53... Kc4 54. Rg6! (54. Rxf4?? exf4 55. Kxf4 Kd4 56. Kg4 Ke3 57. Kxh4 Kf2 $10 { Transposing to the other drawn king and pawn endgame. }) (54. Rc6+?! Kb5 55. Re6 Kc4 { Transposes. }) 54... Kc3 55. Rg4 Bg3!? (55... Kd2!? 56. Rxh4 $18) 56. Rxg3+! hxg3 57. Kxe5 Kd3 58. Kf4 $18 { Finally a king and pawn endgame where white wins. }) 53... Kc4 54. Rxe5?? (54. Rg6! { White should transpose to the 53. Rf6 line here to show the true winning technique. }) 54... Bxe5 55. Kxe5 Kd3 56. Kf4 Ke2 57. Kg4 Kf2 58. Kxh4 Kxg2 59. Kg4 { I only saw this was a draw during analysis. } 59... h5+! 60. Kh4 Kh2 61. Kxh5 Kxh3 $10) 53. Kf5 { [%clk 0:04:00] } 53... Kf7 { [%clk 0:01:00] } (53... Kd7? 54. Re6 Kc7!? (54... Bg3!? 55. Rxh6! $18 (55. Rxe5?? Bxe5 56. Kxe5 Ke7 57. Kf5 Kf7 58. Kg4 Kg6 59. Kxh4 h5 $10)) 55. Rxe5! Bxe5 56. Kxe5 $18 { My king cannot get around white's king and touch the g pawn. }) 54. Ra7+ { [%clk 0:04:00] } 54... Kf8?! { I incorrectly thought that any time Kf6 is played, I can kick the king out with Bg5+. Unfortunately that hangs the e pawn. } { [%clk 0:01:00] } (54... Ke8!? { The best try. At least black is fighting here. } 55. Kf6!? (55. Ke6?! Kd8 56. Rf7 Bg3 $18 { It's not so easy for black to enter a winning king and pawn endgame yet. }) 55... Bg3 56. Re7+ Kd8 57. Ra7 $16 { Still work to be done for white. } (57. Rxe5?? { Once more we get the same endgame. } 57... Bxe5+ 58. Kxe5 Ke7 59. Kf4 Kf6 60. Kg4 Kg6 61. Kxh4 h5! $10)) (54... Kg8?! 55. Kg6 Kf8 56. Rf7+! Kg8 57. Rxf4! exf4 58. Kxh6 { Another simple win. } 58... Kf7 59. Kg5 Ke6 60. Kxh4 Kf5 61. Kh5 Kf6 62. Kg4 Ke5 63. h4 $18) 55. Kf6 { [%clk 0:04:00] } 55... Kg8?! { Now my king is stuck towards the corner. I still thought I was fine here during the game though. } { [%clk 0:00:30] } (55... Bg5+?! 56. Kxe5 $18 { Now my king is truly not getting out since every king and pawn endgame is lost. }) (55... Ke8!? { Better defense, although once again I was afraid that Re7+ lead to a winning king and pawn endgame. } 56. Kg6! { Starting a triangulation that wins a tempo is the way forward. The pressure on the h pawn prevents Bg3 as a defensive idea. } 56... Bg5 57. Ra5 Bf4 58. Ra4! { Now Rxf4 is threatened. } 58... Bg5!? (58... Ke7?! 59. Rxf4! exf4 60. Kxh6 $18) (58... Bg3?! 59. Kxh6 $18) 59. Kf5! Bf4?! 60. Rxf4! exf4 61. Kg6! $18) 56. Rb7 { [%clk 0:04:00] } 56... Bg3 { [%clk 0:00:30] } 57. Rb8+ { [%clk 0:04:00] } 57... Kh7 { [%clk 0:00:30] } 58. Kf7 { I still didn't see the win. } { [%clk 0:04:00] } 58... Bf4 { [%clk 0:00:30] } 59. Re8 { Whenever I get a chance to dream of playing e4, she prevents me before it's possible. } { [%clk 0:04:00] } 59... Bg3 { [%clk 0:00:30] } 60. Rg8! { I still didn't see the win. } { [%clk 0:04:00] } 60... Bf4 { [%clk 0:00:30] } 61. Rg7+! { The key finesse. My king is trapped in the corner. } { [%clk 0:04:00] } 61... Kh8 { [%clk 0:00:30] } 62. Kg6! { Only now did I see the win. White will move the rook along the 7th rank and threaten Ranything8#. There's no zuzgwang required even though my king is not in opposition with her king because I am stuck on the corner of the board.
I thought it would be nice to play out the mate to give her the satisfaction of playing such an impressive endgame. } { [%clk 0:04:00] } 62... e4 { [%clk 0:00:30] } 63. Re7 { [%clk 0:04:00] } 63... Bd6 { [%clk 0:00:30] } 64. Re8+ { [%clk 0:04:00] } 64... Bf8 { [%clk 0:00:30] } 65. Rxf8# { 1-0 White wins. } { We were the final board in the top section to finish. Unfortunately my opponent continued to look unhappy even after winning the game. Not sure what was going on with her, but when I jokingly said "I guess there's not really time to analyze this one before our next round," she just scoffed and walked away. } { [%clk 0:04:00] } 1-0


