{ My opponent was the lowest rated and probably youngest player in the section. He was theoretically only able to play this section because he had surpassed 1900 USCF at an earlier date. An 8 year old 1900 player is scary, especially when he plays a sideline in the opening, gaining time on every move.

Unfortunately, because I was facing the lowest rated player in the field, even a win would not be enough for me to cross 2000 again. My motivation going into this game was pretty low, since results-wise and rating-wise this game would have essentially no effect on my tournament. Ah well, at least I have white. }
1. e4 { [%clk 1:30:00] } 1... e5 { [%clk 1:30:00] } 2. Nf3 { [%clk 1:31:00] } 2... Nc6 { [%clk 1:30:00] } 3. Bb5 { [%clk 1:31:00] } 3... Nf6 { [%clk 1:30:00] } 4. d3 { After many years of back-and-forth on this position, I've decided to play the anti-Berlin and keep more tension in the position. } { [%clk 1:31:00] } 4... d6!? { Black no longer has the option to play the quick d5 lines, equalizing in the center. But now there's a threat of a6+b5+Na5, winning my bishop. } { [%clk 1:30:00] } (4... Bc5!? 5. c3!? (5. O-O!? Nd4 6. Nxd4 Bxd4 7. c3 Bb6 8. Na3 $10 { I had prepared something special in this position as an alternative to the fast d5 lines. }) 5... O-O 6. O-O d5! $10 { One of the most critical lines to force a draw. }) 5. c3!? { Keeping an escape square for my bishop. } { [%clk 1:29:00] } (5. O-O?! a6! { To avoid being worse, I have to take on c6. } 6. Ba4?! (6. Bxc6+ bxc6 7. d4 $10 { I know that this position is supposed to be OK for white if we hadn't wasted a tempo on d3. Here? Must be equal. }) 6... b5 7. Bb3 Na5 $15 { Black has a normal position and wins the bishop pair. }) (5. a3!? a6 6. Bc4 b5 7. Ba2 $10 { White can play with the somewhat fashionable a3+Ba2 stuff as well. }) 5... a6 { [%clk 1:31:00] } 6. Ba4 { [%clk 1:29:00] } (6. Bxc6+?! bxc6 7. O-O $15 { The bishop pair means more than the lead in development. }) 6... b5 { [%clk 1:31:00] } 7. Bb3!? { I wasn't sure if it was smarter to retreat to c2 or b3 during the game. My reasoning for going to b3 was that I wanted to take the sting out of any early d5 lines. } { [%clk 1:26:00] } (7. Bc2?! d5! { This move seemed to force me into a slow Italian game. } 8. Qe2 d4! $10 { If black knows what they are doing here, white cannot get the textbook attack after Nbd2>f1->g3->f5. Black's queenside play can happen too quickly. } (8... Be6!? $10 { The sensible way to play. })) 7... Be7 { [%clk 1:31:00] } (7... d5?! 8. exd5 Nxd5 9. O-O Be7 10. Re1 { White gets the d3 Marshall gambit, up a tempo after } 10... O-O 11. Nxe5 Nxe5 12. Rxe5 c6 13. Re1 Bd6 14. Nd2 Qh4 15. Nf3! $18 { Refuted. }) 8. O-O { [%clk 1:24:00] } 8... O-O { [%clk 1:31:00] } 9. Re1 { Until this point, both sides have been making sensible moves. } { [%clk 1:24:00] } 9... Bb7!? { My opponent played this move almost instantly. I wasn't sure if we were still in theory, but I was happy to see it. I don't have to play d4 so quickly and enter the Zaitsev, where this move makes sense. And in the Chigorin, if I can play d4-d5, this bishop is misplaced. } { [%clk 1:30:00] } (9... Na5! 10. Bc2 c5 11. Nbd2 Nc6 $10 { The masters DB has many games from this position. }) 10. Nbd2 { [%clk 1:22:00] } 10... Na5 { [%clk 1:26:00] } 11. Bc2 { [%clk 1:22:00] } 11... c5 { In my opinion, black is mixing plans. d5 is the break to achieve if your bishop is on b7. } { [%clk 1:24:00] } 12. Nf1 { [%clk 1:16:00] } 12... Re8 { [%clk 1:23:00] } 13. Ng3 { [%clk 1:15:00] } 13... g6 { [%clk 1:22:00] } (13... Bf8?! 14. Bg5!? { The move is somewhat irritating. } 14... h6 15. Bh4! $14 { You do not want to be playing g5 while your pieces are all on the queenside. } 15... g5? 16. Nxg5 hxg5 17. Bxg5 $16 { [%cal Gg3f5,Gd1f3,Gf3g3] }) 14. d4?! { Logical play in the center. But now black gets a reasonable Chigorin since d4 took white two moves to make. } { [%clk 1:09:00] } (14. Bg5!? $14 { Hansen, Eric - Mikhalevski, Victor, 0-1, Canadian op, 2009, https://lichess.org/IBBbZXbY } { Hansen got a good position out of the opening against Big Mikh by playing for b4 and some queenside space. Playing against the bad LSB is a strong idea. }) (14. h3!? Bf8 15. Bg5 h6 16. Bd2 $10 { I could always play within the structure. But if I don't claim the center soon, black will be the one to play d5 and run me off the board. }) 14... Nc6? { A clear mishandling of the position. } { [%clk 1:19:00] } (14... cxd4! { Black needs to open up the position before repositioning the knight in order to prove that this is an improvement over the mainline Chigorin. } 15. cxd4 exd4!? (15... Nc6? 16. d5 Nb4 17. Bb1 a5 18. a3 Na6 $10 19. Bd3! (19. h3? Nc5! { The improvement from the normal Chigorin: black's knight actually returns to c5. }) (19. b4? { In the Chigorin, with the bishop still on c8, this move is playable because black's knight is pinned. Here, this is clearly not the case. } 19... axb4 20. axb4 Nxb4! $17) 19... Qd7 20. Qe2! Nc7 $16 { The knight is in a bad spot again and white has a normal Chigorin bind in the position. }) 16. b3 Nc6 17. Bb2 Rc8 18. Nxd4 $10 { I thought about playing this way during the game. I was reminded of Fischer - Keres, 1959. }) 15. d5! { We now get the normal Chigorin structure, but black has clearly wasted time with the knight, rather than gained time as you would think black is owed, due to white's earlier d2-d3-d4. } { [%clk 1:09:00] } 15... Nb8 { Both the knight and LSB are now clearly bad pieces. } { [%clk 1:19:00] } 16. b3!? { Taking the sting out of c4. Black's Nbd7->c5 plan is not easy to achieve. A good move, but I think I shouldn't have spent so long on it. } { [%clk 0:57:00] } (16. a4?! c4 $14 { I didn't want to allow this transformation, where Nbd7->c5 is inevitable. We're essentially transposing to the main line of the Chigorin. But of course, that's a position I've studied and white is slightly better there. }) (16. h3!? c4 17. b4 a5! { A critical move I didn't have an answer to during the game. The more I thought about this position (and similar positions) though, the more resources I was finding for white. } 18. a4! $14 { Found later during analysis. See other similar lines where white is doing well. }) 16... Nbd7 { [%clk 1:18:00] } (16... c4! { Honestly, I thought black should go ahead and do this anyway - this move or next. } 17. bxc4!? (17. b4!? a5! { This being the crucial point. White cannot maintain b4 without allowing files to open for black's pieces. } 18. a3? (18. a4!? { A move I was trying to evaluate during the game. } 18... axb4 19. cxb4 bxa4 20. Bxa4 $14 { I didn't think I wanted to allow black this c file pressure. Black's knight though cannot ever use the c5 square. White's pawn is probably scarier than black's pawn. }) 18... axb4 19. cxb4 $10) 17... bxc4 18. Be3 $14 { White gets some play here, but black will eventually get in the Nc5 move. }) 17. h3 { Preparing Be3. It's now or never with c4. } { [%clk 0:56:00] } 17... Qc7?! { So it's never with c4. } { [%clk 1:17:00] } (17... c4! $14 { Similar to the previous lines, I can't hold together the pawn on b4. }) 18. Be3 { [%clk 0:53:00] } (18. a4?! bxa4 19. Rxa4 Nb6 20. Ra1 c4 21. b4 a5! $13 { I was annoyed that black has this shot here. My a pawn is not strong enough if I take on a5, and so black has stirred up some trouble here. }) 18... Rac8 { Tempting me to play a4 now. } { [%clk 1:13:00] } (18... c4?! 19. b4! { Now this is playable for white. } 19... a5 20. a4!? { But once more this is the more active move you want to make in this position. } (20. a3!? $14 { Even this move is playable again since the rook is defended on a1. }) 20... axb4 21. cxb4 bxa4 22. Bxa4 { Similar to the earlier c4 line, but white is better coordinated. }) 19. Qd2 { At this point in the game, I knew I had consolidated my advantage and was thinking about several famous games with different plans.
The first was Karpov - Unzicker, 1974, where white played the famous Ba7 to control the a file. This idea doesn't work in this position because black's queen can directly challenge the bishop on a7 in combination with a rook on a8. So the idea of a4 and tripling on the a file isn't immediately crushing for white.
The next was Tal - Spassky, 1980, where white had a beautiful attack on the kingside kicking off with Rf1+f4.
The third was Zherebukh - Caruana, 2017, which followed a similar pattern to Tal's game but had a more refined f4 pawn break.
Seeing that there were two beautiful kingside attacks from a similar structure, I figured I would head over to the kingside with some of my pieces, focusing in particular on the weakened dark squares. } { [%clk 0:52:00] } (19. a4!? { Thematic and good. } 19... bxa4? 20. Rxa4 Nb6 21. Ra1 c4 { For some reason I was "scared" of allowing black this move. But it accomplishes nothing after the obvious } 22. b4! $16 { The fact that I couldn't see that a5 immediately drops a pawn to Rxa5 from afar shows how tired I was at this point in the tournament. }) 19... Bf8 { [%clk 1:07:00] } 20. Rf1!? { A flexible move. I'm preparing to move the f3 knight and play f4 at the right moment. In the Zherebukh game, he crucially recaptured on f4 with the rook, even allowing Be5 Raf1 as an exchange sacrifice. } { [%clk 0:46:00] } (20. a4! $16 { The most normal move. I didn't want to even allow a hint of queenside counterplay though while I conduct my kingside attack. But in the Ruy Lopez, white's space advantage is so amazing precisely because we can play on both sides of the board so easily. Again, my fears of bxa4 giving black some counterplay show how poor my calculation was at this point in the tournament. }) (20. Kh1!? $14 { In expectation of playing f4, I didn't want my king on the open diagonal. But this is quite slow and also gets in the way of a potential Nh1 maneuver. Sometimes, fancy is not good. }) 20... h5 { A normal, but annoying move. Now in some lines my knight gets kicked with h4 } { [%clk 1:02:00] } 21. Nh4?! { h4 is directly prevented. I'm going for the f4 pawn break next. However, this is all a bit rushed. I should have opened up more opportunities to infiltrate on the queenside with a4 instead. What is black doing in the meantime? } { [%clk 0:37:00] } (21. a4! { Thematic and good. } 21... Bg7 (21... bxa4?! 22. Rxa4 Nb6 23. Raa1 c4 24. b4 $16 { The same line continues to be good for white. a5 is once again not playable. }) 22. Ra2!? $16 { First I can poke around on the queenside, threatening axb5. Once once black has brought the pieces over to defend should I hit black with the Nh4+f4 combo.
I didn't have the stamina or patience for a plan like this in the game. }) (21. Ng5!? { The most normal way to prepare f4. } 21... h4 22. Nh1 { I suppose this is probably the best square now. After f4, the knight is heading towards g4 via f2. What I didn't recall from the Tal game is that when h4 was playable, Nf1 was still an available square. So perhaps I rushed Rf1 a little here. }) 21... Be7! { Setting up Nxe4 as a discovery, thus preventing f4 for one more move. At this point though I saw a naked king and like a bull seeing red decided to go for it. } { [%clk 1:00:00] } (21... Nh7?! 22. f4 exf4 23. Rxf4! { The recapture I was considering during the game. } 23... Bh6 24. Raf1 Bxf4 25. Bxf4 $16 { Now we're cooking! e5 and Nxg6 and Nhf5 and Bh6 and Rxf7 are all in the air. White's gotta be taking this one home. }) 22. Bg5?! { Doubling down on the kingside play is incorrect. I'm preventing Nxe4, so that f4 is again my next move. Sadly, I didn't see black's next move coming. } { [%clk 0:34:00] } (22. Nf3!? { I should probably just repeat } 22... Bf8 23. a4 $16 { Nh4+f4 can wait until black is less coordinated in the defense. }) (22. f4!? Nxe4 23. Nxe4 Bxh4 { Black wins the pawn. } 24. f5! $14 { But hilariously, even this position is not so clear. Black doesn't have many defenders near his king. }) 22... Qd8! { Once more, Nxe4 is back on - this time it's my bishop that's loose. The fact that black can generate these threats proves that I didn't do enough queenside massaging to be able to get away with the beautiful kingside attack that Tal or Zherebukh performed. I knew that I had already messed up the attack, but I didn't see a way to avoid Nxe4 without getting kicked back. } { [%clk 0:59:00] } 23. Nhf5? { Disgusted with how easily black has defended any haphazard attack so far, I decided to pull the trigger on the thematic piece sacrifice just to muddy the waters. This should definitely not work. } { [%clk 0:30:00] } (23. Nf3!? { Avoids the immediate tactics, but black has several reasonable options here. } 23... Nh7!? { The more sensible option that I predicted. } (23... h4? { I thought this was playable during the game. Oof my calculation was in the toilet at this point in time. } 24. Bxh4 Nxe4?! { The issue I saw during the game. White has many great moves here though. For instance: } (24... Nxd5?! 25. exd5 Bxh4 26. Qh6 $16 { But this is fantastic for white too. }) 25. Nxe4 Bxh4 26. Nxd6 $18) 24. Be3 (24. Bh6 h4 $14 { I did not like getting kicked back here. }) 24... h4 $14 { I haven't traded anything here, so the attack can still happen in round 2. But this is just pathetic. }) (23. f4!? Nh7! { The problem. I can't avoid the trades anymore with Bh6 because my knight on h4 once again is loose. } (23... exf4? 24. Qxf4 $16 { Out of range of black's knight. Now the attack is on for real. }) 24. Bxe7 Qxe7 $10 { If only I had time for fxe5 and Qh6. Then the Nf5 sacrifices would make sense. Here it's just too early... }) 23... gxf5 { [%clk 0:58:00] } 24. Nxf5 { Importantly, I had refuted both Nxe4 and Nxd5 before arriving at this position. If black does nothing, my slow but inevitable plan of f4 and doubling rooks on the f file towards black's king is actually quite strong.
To my opponent's credit, he correctly slowed down in this position. He thought for nearly 20 minutes before pulling the trigger on a tempting line that I thought had refuted.
During the 20 minute think, I could feel myself hyperventilating. I got up from the board several times trying to calm myself down... to no avail. While I was light-headed in the corner of the hall, focusing on slow breathing, I noticed several other people in the section get up from their games and check out the piece sacrifice. I'm not sure if that made me more or less nervous. } { [%clk 0:30:00] } 24... Nxd5! { I had "refuted" this move a long time ago. To my surprise, my opponent plays this losing attempt!? What's going on? Only now did I see that my supposed refutation itself is completely refuted. } { [%clk 0:41:00] } (24... Nh7!? { During the game, I actually thought this was a solid way for black to give back material but defuse the attack. I only saw this defense though during my opponent's 20 minute think. } 25. Bxe7 Rxe7 26. Qh6!? f6! { Another move I hadn't seen from afar but was sad to spot during my opponent's 20 minute think. } (26... Qf8?! 27. Qxd6! $16 { Only seen in analysis. Thankfully this tempting defense doesn't work either. }) 27. Qg6+?! (27. Rae1!! { SF alert. } 27... Qf8 28. Qxh5 { The engine is a savage. Apparently white is able to casually swing the rook up and over to the g file and there's nothing black can do in the meantime! } 28... Rc7 29. Re3 Nb6 30. Rg3+ Rg7 31. Nxg7 Rxg7 32. Rxg7+ Qxg7 33. f4! $16) 27... Kh8 28. Nxe7 Qxe7 $15 { White just doesn't have enough here either. }) (24... c4?! { This line is merely included as an example of how the attack can progress: } 25. f4! { My dreams of an attack would finally be realized. } 25... exf4? 26. Qxf4 cxb3!? (26... Ne5? 27. Nxe7+ Qxe7 28. Bxf6 $18) 27. Qg3 Kh7 28. Nxe7! Qxe7 29. Rxf6! Nxf6 30. Bxf6 Qxf6 31. e5+ $18) (24... Kh7?! { Another nothing move also shows how my attack can continue. } 25. f4! Ng8 26. Qe2 Bxg5 27. fxg5 { h5, d6, and f7 are all falling. } 27... Qxg5 28. Nxd6 $16 { [%cal Gd6e8,Gd6f7,Gd6c8,Gd6b7,Gf1f7] }) (24... Nxe4?? { Another move I refuted before pulling the trigger on the knight sacrifice. } 25. Nxe7+ { The check is important. } 25... Qxe7 26. Bxe4 $18 { White's DSB is now only hit once - not twice. Black has simply given back the piece for nothing. White's attack is just beginning. }) 25. Bxe7 { I thought for a further 10 minutes before continuing on with a new way forward. } { [%clk 0:20:00] } (25. Nh6+? { For a brief moment I thought I had this option to bail out for a draw. } 25... Kf8! $19 { There is no follow-up, and black is winning. } (25... Kh8?? 26. Nxf7+ $18) (25... Kh7?? 26. exd5+ $16) (25... Kg7?! 26. Nf5+ { Repeating. } 26... Kg8 $10 { White has a draw unless black finds Kf8. } (26... Kf8? 27. Bh6+ Kg8 28. exd5 $18) (26... Kg6?? 27. Bxe7! Nxe7 28. Qh6#))) 25... Nxe7 { Black has achieved his dream of removing a key attacker and won a center pawn. Is hope completely lost? } { [%clk 0:41:00] } 26. Nxd6! { Completely changing tactics. I'm no longer going after the king. Instead, I'm taking a bunch of pawns and hoping that my two pieces for the rook sacrifice will give me enough for equality. During the game, I no longer believed in my position, especially because I could tell that I was not seeing the board clearly anymore. At least my opponent hadn't completely refuted my sacrifice...
My opponent offered me a draw from this position. I told him he had to make his move first but I would consider it. I was delighted to have him offer a draw though because I was sure I was worse after Rc7, the move I anticipated. } { [%clk 0:20:00] } (26. Qh6?? { I reached this position before I sacrificed my knight on f5. From afar, was sure there was no way to defend the mate on g7. } 26... Nxf5 $19 { Oops. That certainly defends it! This is the move I couldn't see from afar when I first played Nhf5. }) (26. Qg5+?? Ng6 27. Qh6 Qf6! $19 { It's so sad when your brilliancy get defeated so easily. }) 26... Rb8? $10 { Only now did I accept the draw offered last move by my opponent. I was so relieved to escape from this game. I haven't felt this blind at the board in a long time, having missed moves and misevaluated lines left and right.
Hilariously though, my opponent's move isn't that good because now I have more opportunities to play on without capturing back the exchange. The fact that I didn't even notice any of these possibilities points to how dead I was at the board.
After the game, we did a quick post-mortem blindfolded. I was impressed with my opponent's clarity of thought. As opposed to other 8 years olds I've faced, he was able to explain his thoughts and justify his moves quite clearly. Good positional sense and reasonable tactical vision too, even blindfolded. He is certainly a player to watch out for in the future!
I went 1.5/4 overall, gaining a few rating points. In the middle of the tournament, I reached as high as 2005 USCF, barely crossing 2000 for the first time. Even though the last two games did not go my way, I'm still happy I didn't drop out just to have the 2000 officially on my history. These have been interesting games to analyze for sure. } { [%clk 0:39:00] } (26... Rc7! { The move I expected. } 27. Nxe8 { Now taking the rook is the way to go. } (27. Rad1?! Ng6 { Re6 is coming so I really do need to take the rook for real. } 28. Nxe8 Qxe8 $17) 27... Qxe8 $15 { I assumed I was worse in this position. Still, we have to make the best of it sometimes - at least white isn't resigning any time soon. }) (26... Nf8? { Thankfully, you can't take advantage of the pin on the d file. } { [%cal Gd8d2] } 27. Qg5+! Neg6 28. Qxd8 Rcxd8 29. Nxb7 $16 { [%cal Gb7a5,Gb7c5] }) 27. Rad1! { Black cannot easily untangle. } 27... Rf8!? (27... Ng6?? 28. Nxe8 Qxe8 29. Qxd7 $18) 28. Qh6! { Here's a spectacular engine line showcasing how white is crushing it here. } 28... Nc8 29. Rd3! { [%cal Gd3g3] } 29... h4 (29... Nxd6?? 30. Rg3+ Qg5 31. Rxg5#) 30. Nf5 Qf6 31. Qh5! { With too many threats. Black cannot challenge just these three attacking pieces in time. } 31... Ne7 32. Rd6! $18 { Winning at least the queen. } 32... Qh8?! 33. Qg5+ Ng6 34. Rxg6+ fxg6 35. Qxg6+ Qg7 36. Qxg7# 1/2-1/2


